{
  "doc_id": "17122",
  "text": "CF lung disease is generally diffuse and bilateral although inhomogeneity is recognised between different lobes and rarely disease may become markedly severe in specific lobes or in one lung [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . If a collapsed/consolidated lung is not reinflated then a vicious cycle of mucus impaction, infection and inflammation can lead to irreversible damage [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . In extreme cases a phenomenon known as 'destroyed lung' may occur where an entire lung is irreversibly damaged, contributing little to ventilation yet causing significant problems with chronic infection [CITATION_5] . Potentially life-threatening complications may occur including septicaemia, haemoptysis, empyema, pulmonary-systemic shunting and pulmonary hypertension [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Surgical pneumonectomy to remove the destroyed lung may be indicated but is not without associated risks and importantly is only a viable option if the contralateral lung is not severely involved. On occasions one specific lobe may be causing severe problems and consideration may be given to the pros and cons of lobectomy in such cases [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
